{"Title": "Developments for resonance ionization laser spectroscopy of the heaviest elements at SHIP", "Year": 2016, "Source": "Nucl Instrum Methods Phys Res Sect B", "Volume": "383", "Issue": null, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": 115, "PageEnd": 122, "CitedBy": 17, "DOI": "10.1016/j.nimb.2016.06.001", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=84976911504&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 2016 Elsevier B.V.The experimental determination of atomic levels and the first ionization potential of the heaviest elements (Z\u2a7e100) is key to challenge theoretical predictions and to reveal changes in the atomic shell structure. These elements are only artificially produced in complete-fusion evaporation reactions at on-line facilities such as the GSI in Darmstadt at a rate of, at most, a few atoms per second. Hence, highly sensitive spectroscopic methods are required. Laser spectroscopy is one of the most powerful and valuable tools to investigate atomic properties. In combination with a buffer-gas filled stopping cell, the Radiation Detected Resonance Ionization Spectroscopy (RADRIS) technique provides the highest sensitivity for laser spectroscopy on the heaviest elements. The RADRIS setup, as well as the measurement procedure, have been optimized and characterized using the \u03b1-emitter 155Yb in on-line conditions, resulting in an overall efficiency well above 1%. This paves the way for a successful search of excited atomic levels in nobelium and heavier elements.", "AuthorKeywords": ["Gas stopping cell", "Nobelium", "Radiation Detected Resonance Ionization Spectroscopy", "Resonance ionization spectroscopy", "Ytterbium"], "IndexKeywords": ["Excited atomic level", "Experimental determination", "First ionization potentials", "Fusion-evaporation reactions", "Gas stopping", "Measurement procedures", "Resonance ionization spectroscopy", "Spectroscopic method"], "DocumentType": "Journal", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 0, "EID": "2-s2.0-84976911504", "SubjectAreas": [["Nuclear and High Energy Physics", "PHYS", "3106"], ["Instrumentation", "PHYS", "3105"]], "AuthorData": {"55932921800": {"Name": "Lautenschl\u00e4ger F.", "AuthorID": "55932921800", "AffiliationID": "60008155", "AffiliationName": "GSI Helmholtzzentrum f\u00fcr Schwerionenforschung"}, "55933452000": {"Name": "Chhetri P.", "AuthorID": "55933452000", "AffiliationID": "60008155", "AffiliationName": "GSI Helmholtzzentrum f\u00fcr Schwerionenforschung"}, "57190048601": {"Name": "Kaleja O.", "AuthorID": "57190048601", "AffiliationID": "60011226", "AffiliationName": "Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt"}, "57202862004": {"Name": "Walther T.", "AuthorID": "57202862004", "AffiliationID": "60011226", "AffiliationName": "Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt"}, "55143078600": {"Name": "Ackermann D.", "AuthorID": "55143078600", "AffiliationID": "60008155", "AffiliationName": "GSI Helmholtzzentrum f\u00fcr Schwerionenforschung"}, "8842274300": {"Name": "Block M.", "AuthorID": "8842274300", "AffiliationID": "60031216", "AffiliationName": "Johannes Gutenberg Universit\u00e4t Mainz"}, "57206856027": {"Name": "Clark A.", "AuthorID": "57206856027", "AffiliationID": "60008155", "AffiliationName": "GSI Helmholtzzentrum f\u00fcr Schwerionenforschung"}, "35317310400": {"Name": "Droese C.", "AuthorID": "35317310400", "AffiliationID": "60021311", "AffiliationName": "Ernst Moritz Arndt Universit\u00e4t Greifswald"}, "24338075200": {"Name": "Giacoppo F.", "AuthorID": "24338075200", "AffiliationID": "109504313", "AffiliationName": "Helmholtz Institut Mainz"}, "57191830201": {"Name": "G\u00f6tz S.", "AuthorID": "57191830201", "AffiliationID": "109504313", "AffiliationName": "Helmholtz Institut Mainz"}, "7003327706": {"Name": "He\u00dfberger F.", "AuthorID": "7003327706", "AffiliationID": "109504313", "AffiliationName": "Helmholtz Institut Mainz"}, "14826956100": {"Name": "Khuyagbaatar J.", "AuthorID": "14826956100", "AffiliationID": "109504313", "AffiliationNa